The paper deals with complexity reductions and combinatorial gadgets, which are topics commonly studied in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of these gadgets to prove a complexity dichotomy theorem suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The study of directed graphs and their partition function may also suggest a connection to graph theory (cs.DS) and graph algorithms (cs.CG). Finally, the use of complex-valued binary functions may suggest a connection to computational geometry (cs.CG) or game theory (cs.GT).
